##My mother-in-law's last mass during the epidemic

Micro Signal Xinminzhoukan

Function description, depth and angle —— this is what we can do.

The Dutch even seem to be a little cool, not as warm and romantic as southern Europeans. But when it comes to helping others, they usually do their best, no strings attached.

By Wang Qiaoli

To face up to the new coronaviruses

At seven o'clock in the evening, the Dutch waited in front of the television for the Prime Minister's Mark Rutte speech.

In a country of 17 million people, there were 1,413 infections and 24 deaths. Medical supplies are tight, rumours are rife, and the "Orange Army" , always known for its good health and big heart, is confused and worried.

My sister in law, Marianne, was standing outside the door, talking to my husband through a meter, discussing my mother in Law's illness.

The mother-in-law, 88, has been in poor health for several years and has been living in a hospice. Since last month, she has been feverish, sicker, and unresponsive. The sister-in-law went to see her, and the mother-in-law did not recognize the eldest daughter who had taken the greatest care of her and was the proudest of her.

The question for the sister-in-law and her husband is: will she get the help she needs if her mother-in-law's condition worsens in the new crown pneumonia epidemic in the Netherlands? Hospice each time only one family members regularly go in to visit, in case the mother-in-law happened to be, the family is not in how to do?

Teenage mother-in-law

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Mother-in-law behind the car window, taken six months ago

On March 16th, the country faced its first day of a new coronavirus. As of Monday, schools are closed, restaurants and cafes are closed. The government advises people to travel less and stay at home as much as possible. Before that, parties of more than 100 people were called off and cinemas closed. My Film Documentary, Le Seng (co-directed by Roman Tam) , which I produced and directed, is scheduled for March 17 at Lumiere Cinema, the largest art house in the Netherlands. Just two days before its release, the government decided to shut down all venues for gatherings of more than 100 people, and the film became part of history after it was forced to be delayed.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Due to the outbreak, Lumiere Cinema has been forced to delay the screening of "Le Seng" and the original 17 evening dialogue with the director

"I don't have easy news for you. The Netherlands is an open country. The virus wave is coming, and it's not going to go away, " the Mark Rutte said, explaining three possible scenarios and the government's options.

The first possibility is to build up a population immunity while minimizing the spread of the virus. In this way, 60% to 70% of the population will be infected, and it will take months.

The second possibility is to allow the virus to spread, overloading the health care system and leaving the elderly and other at-risk groups without help.

The third option is to fight the virus, under the command of Death Suguo. That sounds appealing, and it could paralyze the country for months or more than a year. More companies will fail and more people will lose their jobs.

It is the Dutch government's choice to build up population immunity in a controlled and gradual manner. The Netherlands is on the same side as Germany, France and Britain, rather than being as radical as Italy and Spain.

For a country with a long tradition of rationalism, such a choice is hardly surprising. Separating the defense system from the combat (therapeutic) system is actually consistent with the long-standing European idea of hierarchical medicine.

The Dutch government has opted for a combination of strict control and mass immunization to avoid overloading the health system

People all over the world know that in Holland, if you just get sick with a cold, you can't go to the hospital. Patients with mild illness can only see a family doctor, went to the basic is wasted, the probability or let you go home empty-handed rest. The doctor's judgment of the severity of the disease, and our conventional understanding is not the same.

I remember when I gave birth to my eldest son, I went home the afternoon after giving birth. The next day she had a postpartum fever and was shivering. Sir called the hospital in a fit of anxiety. The hospital sent a male doctor and an intern to the home, after a careful examination, suggested I use ice pack head, let Mr. Go to the store for me to buy two ice cream. I want to laugh and cry, this is how the original method Ah!

Later, unable to resist his insistence, I painfully ate an ice cream cone, the temperature slowly fell. Physical Cooling, rather than medication, is often the first option for Dutch doctors.

As I understand it, China and Europe are playing different games against each other on the pitch. China has taken an aggressive approach to the virus. Europe is playing all-defensive football, although it started off a bit fuzzy, and that doesn't mean it isn't kicking hard. Sweden, which has been heavily criticised in Chinese newspapers, has also adopted a "Total Defence" strategy, relying on low-risk groups to heal themselves and free up resources and space for those at risk.

"If the end were tomorrow, I'd still be planting my own apple trees today, " I said when asked about the uncertainty of the world in a September 2019 documentary by a reporter for TV 1 in Limburg province, the Netherlands. It's always been one of my convictions that I've forgotten where I came from.

Half a year, China and the United States trade war side talks while fighting, after years of Britain finally leave the European Union, the global outbreak of coronavirus, the United States twice a week fuse. The scale and frequency of these uncertain events makes it difficult to see the jigsaw puzzle of our time and our situation.

From a longer timeline, as a former journalist living abroad, I experienced SARS 17 years ago, fought alongside my colleagues, and did a cover story in the Xinmin Weekly called for transparent administration. Even today, that set of stories still stands up to scrutiny.

Seventeen years later, as a director of documentaries and stage shows, I was in Maastricht, the Netherlands, responding to the government's "Home Quarantine" decree and again experiencing, in my own way, the outbreak from a single spark.

Social support at the critical moment

A German friend of mine wrote about his neighbor's preparations for "grounding" :

Belndt, 78, lives in North rhine-westphalia, Germany. He has a son, a daughter and a grandson. After breakfast, the old man began to plan the first step of his epidemic prevention work: If my wife and I were to be separated for two weeks, what food, clothing, and shelter we absolutely needed, what we had, what we needed to buy, such as purchasing, what shop when the least people, infection rate is the least, what shop can buy online, roughly how much time. How many essential medicines are needed, how many are nearing their expiration date and need to be updated, what is the nearest emergency room equipment, if not available, where is the next point, how long will it take to drive..

After all that was done, plans were made for daughters and sons in law: Daughters in Berlin, busloads of buses, what alternatives to travel were available to reduce the risk of infection, and which companies were hosting online conferences in Berlin, can I suggest my daughter's company to implement telecommuting, in case it doesn't work, who can write a note... after all the careful planning, start to see what the son's family needs, what contingency plans should be made, how to make it happen... while humming a tune and sipping coffee, Bernd writes his deployment into "to do lists" with contact addresses and phone numbers... He's working hard, and his son-in-law calls and says he can't get a mask, "I placed an order two weeks ago, and I'll be there this afternoon. I'll send you five of them. Use Them... "

This strong ability to organize personal affairs is common in Germany and the Netherlands.

When my mother-in-law was in good health, she would take a notepad with her everywhere, which was always filled with "shopping list" , "To-do list" , "To-do list" and so on. She managed her family like a librarian, and I couldn't do it in my next life, so I just gave up.

Our neighbors have long established a WHATSAPP community for dozens of families on the street. In the crowd which family has the critically ill patient, which family has the young and middle-aged, all statistics are clear. Who may be most in need of help, and who can help on what day and at what specific time. In our mailbox, we also received a note from a local college student who offered to help us for free.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The town before the outbreak, the Maastricht, where we lived

The Dutch seem even a little cool, not as warm and romantic as southern Europeans, but when it comes to helping others, they generally do their best without strings attached.

Once I hurt my arm, a neighbor found out and quietly mowed my front lawn. Worried that I was starving, other Dutch colleagues sent soup and homemade cakes.

Throughout the day, thousands of people have signed up as medical volunteers, including retired health care workers and those trained in health care but otherwise engaged in work, medical students and others.

Kindergartens and schools in the Netherlands are not completely closed. If there are two people in a family who are engaged in much needed work, such as health care, logistics, etc. , the school still accepts their children to attend school and uses a group approach to do its best to keep them healthy.

Two months ago, I flew back to Amsterdam from Beijing. Looking at the domestic news, every day is sad, worried. "The country is in trouble, every man is responsible" , as an absent person, at the beginning I was a deep sense of powerlessness swallowed. Later, to see the domestic "one difficult eight-way support" of the feat, and countless personal dedication and sacrifice, just have a lot of confidence: China will win.

I, too, am not pessimistic about the country's ability to fight the epidemic, with its strong individual organization and Social Solidarity at critical moments.

A pre-arranged last mass

After reading the Prime Minister's speech, my sister-in-law Marian and my husband agreed to arrange a last mass for my mother-in-law as soon as possible.

Her mother-in-law lived a life of hard work and frugality, survived the Second World War and raised five children. From the daughter of a nobleman in the civil war, to the housewife who had to keep an eye on household expenses and mend pots and pans, she was proud of it, but also unwilling.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The mother-in-law's teenager (the little girl in the middle of the front row)

At the age of eighty, she wanted to finish her college economics course and learn to drive and see the world, but that was a dream. She soon became forgetful and unable to take care of herself.

She was a devout Catholic all her life. It would be difficult for her and her family if she died before the pastor's last mass.

The development of the epidemic has turned the elderly in nursing homes into susceptible groups. Only one visitor at a time, including the pastor.

So when the priest took her thin hand in his gloved hand, and said to her in his muzzled mouth, "God bless you, you will be rewarded for your kindness and devotion in another world, " No family could be there for her.

Maybe she can still want to say but unable to say, maybe she wants to see everyone, convey this last love and give up.

But in March 2020, with the new pneumonia epidemic, everything was different..

Founder of new salt media, documentary film and Stage Director. He lives in the Netherlands and was a political correspondent for Xinmin Weekly. Music Documentary Film "Le Seng" has been selected in the Netherlands, Germany, the United States and other international film festivals
